data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three patterns the skill identifies:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block rolling back | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeping thread alive for `finally` | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check; no longer needed |

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work ŌĆö migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed; loop condition will exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive, there's nothing else to do ŌĆö
        // Thread.Abort doesn't exist in .NET 8.
        // The thread will exit at its next cancellation checkpoint.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

## Key changes explained

**1. `Thread.Abort()` ŌåÆ `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. Replace with cooperative cancellation.

**2. `ThreadAbortException` ŌåÆ `OperationCanceledException`**
Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid catching unrelated exceptions. Your rollback logic moves here unchanged.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` ŌåÆ removed entirely**
No equivalent needed. With cooperative cancellation the thread stays alive ŌĆö the loop just checks `IsCancellationRequested` on the next iteration.

**4. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` ŌåÆ `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish, unlike `Sleep` which blindly waits and hopes.

**5. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token**
This is the most critical pitfall. If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), cancellation will **not interrupt it** unless you pass the token through:

```csharp
// If using BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel

// If using a manual wait:
// Replace: _signal.WaitOne();
// With:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

---

## Common pitfalls for this migration

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | `Cancel()` only works if the blocked code checks it. A bare `socket.Read()` or `Console.ReadLine()` will never wake up. Use async overloads or `WaitHandle`. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers/callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for 30 seconds without checking, it won't stop for 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `catch` block here is correct because we're at the top-level loop. Don't swallow it deeper in the call chain. |
